Preheat oven to 425 degrees. Halve, peel, and thinly slice the @red onion{1}. Strip the @thyme{1%sprig} leaves off the sprig. Halve the @grape tomatoes{1%bunch}.

In a #small baking dish{}, toss the red onion and grape tomatoes with the thyme leaves, @olive oil{1/2%tbsp}, and a pinch of @salt{} and @pepper{}. Place in the oven for ~{15%minutes}, until tomatoes soften and onion is slightly caramelized.

Meanwhile, drain and halve the @artichoke hearts{1%jar}. Mince or grate the @garlic{2%cloves}. Coarsely chop the @parsley{1/4%bunch}. Zest and juice the @lemon{1}. Drain and rinse the @cannellini beans{1%can}. Cut the @chicken breasts{2} into 1/2-inch thick strips.

In a #medium bowl{}, toss the chicken with garlic, lemon zest, half the lemon juice, and @olive oil{1/2%tbsp}. Season with salt and pepper.

In a #small bowl{}, combine @panko breadcrumbs{1%cup}, @mozzarella cheese{1/2%cup}, half the parsley, and @olive oil{2%tsp}. Season with salt and pepper.

Heat @olive oil{1/2%tbsp} in a #large pan{} over high heat. Working in batches, cook the chicken strips for about ~{4%minutes}, turning occasionally, until golden brown but not yet cooked through.

Add the chicken to the #baking dish{} along with the cannellini beans, artichokes, and remaining lemon juice. Toss to combine. Top with the panko mixture and return to the oven for another ~{5-7%minutes}, until chicken is cooked through and panko is golden brown.

Serve the cassoulet right out of the oven and sprinkle with remaining parsley!

> We've taken cassoulet - a traditionally slow-cooked French bean casserole - and made it delicious in under 35 minutes. You'll get the same richness from thyme-roasted tomatoes, caramelized onion, and marinated chicken. Oh, and let's not forget about that cheesy breadcrumb topping. This sure ain't your Momma's casserole!